description.plain:
In a statement accompanying the song, Tomberlin said “‘happy accident’ is about relational obscurity. Trying to sort out who you are or who you were to someone. Is this relationship romantic or is it just sex? Do you want to spend time with me or are you just bored? Do I make my own decisions that are good for me or are my decisions predominantly based on what I think you might want or need? I was kind of walking through moments in previous relationships in my life. I wanna know why someone wants to get to know me. Do you want to know me or just your idea of me? Do I want to know you or just my idea of you?”

https://pitchfork.com/news/tomberlin-announces-new-album-and-tour-shares-video-for-new-song-happy-accident-watch/

annotations:
Is my love worth something?
 ’Cause it don’t feel so free
 Always loving everyone
 In love I expect nothing
She gives up much for her love interests, but they don’t reciprocate those sacrifices at all. This is telling of both the other person and her own ability to (or rather, not to) advocate for herself.

You tell me that I’m easy
 You say I seem “so free”
Because of her willingness to drop her own desires and needs, she comes across as someone agreeable and “easy” to work with, but in reality she is trapped by denying her own needs.

You asked me not to leave
 You alone so I listened
 Till you forgot your misery
Their partner was in a bad mental health state and asked that she stay with them. She did with the consequence of not pursuing her own needs and dreams.
